TextBody:
Hello Gary,

Thank you for contacting Netwrix Technical Support. 

To help us streamline the troubleshooting process and resolve your issue more efficiently, please provide the following information:  

What is the impact of the issue on your business? 
Who is affected by this issue? 
What steps to troubleshoot the issue have already been taken? 
What are you trying to do or accomplish? 
Is this a new configuration, data collection or report? 
If no, has anything changed in your environment since the last time it worked? 
When did this issue start?  
What are the steps to reproduce? 
What software is currently installed - run this command from an admin Powershell prompt:
Get-CimInstance -Class Win32_Product |Where-Object {($_.Name -Like "Stealth*" -or $_.Name -like "Netwrix*" -or $_.Name -like "Postg*" -or ` $_.Name -like "Python*")} -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue

Please perform the follow steps and upload the resulting Artifacts:

Enable Debug Logging
From the NEA Console > Settings > Application
Set Log Level to Debug
Rerun jobs that are failing to collect logs in full detail. Return Log level to warning afterwards.


Please provide logs from the following locations: 
Enterprise Auditor Console: %SAInstallDir%SADatabaseLogsApplication 
Access Information Center (11.6): C:Program FilesSTEALTHbitsAccess Information Center 
Access Information (11.5): C:inetpubwwwrootStealthAUDIT Compliance 

Export of Job(s) – note jobs may be nested under multiple Groups:
Right click on the Job or Job Group experiencing problems and select Export. This creates .zip file containing all logs and configuration settings of your jobs that we can import and review.


From the Job Status Export the Messages Table, CSV is preferred: 
 

Thank you,

Scottie Taylor
Technical Support Engineer

TextBody:
Hello Gary,

Thank you for taking the time to meet today.

Today we:

Reviewed the FSDFS System Scan and discovered errors when targeting the One Domain Controller Per Domain host list versus the DFS Host. Once the DFS server was targeted we were able to get a successful scan and populated updated DFS Namespace information with a successful FSAA Bulk Import. We then tested this information within the AIC with a fresh Bulk Import and was able to run a search against the new DFS Namespace target path. We further tested this information by running a SQL query filtering against an old host and wasn't able to generate any entries but was able to generate entries running a query against the new host. 

Our next steps are:

Further investigate the file structure in the AIC and FSAA system scan against the desired hosts.

Please use this link to schedule our next meeting at your convenience

https://nwxcorp.my.salesforce-sites.com/cts?Id=khMaVwwK9jSPcsxT9x7ITSXIVeIFWoXU49eEwQ9glo8-Z&MeetingID=W6uEEUeRkMPZt59nus.PvkoF9URlQbRwH9UO7qUeydE-Z

Thank you,

TextBody:
Hi Gary,

Thank you for the updated information. Technically, the Namespace would be created on the DFS server or replication enabled pointing to the DFS server and NEA is only using the FSDFS system scan to scan the target servers Namespace. I would recommend verifying if NEA is pulling that path from the DFS server by reviewing the results node from the most recent scan or running a target query against the FSDFS_Links table for that resource path. The AIC can't add resources but it can add a resource owner to an already indexed resource path from the DFS server. 

Thank you,

Scottie Taylor
Technical Support Engineer

Hi Gary,

Thank you for the updated information. I will include this in the ticket. If you're not seeing the path in the database then its not going to be displayed in the AIC as that's the reference the AIC uses to build its file structure. I would verify that the namespace is available on the DFS server. Then you'd need to get a successful FSDFS system scan, FSAA system scan and a FSAA Bulk Import before it will display in the AIC. I have tested this method in my lab and have gotten a few successful scans. I have provided screenshots below:





Thank you,

Scottie Taylor
Technical Support Engineer

TextBody:
Hello Gary,

Yes, from my tests the paths should be shared within the namespace. Then running the FSDFS system scan against the DFS server and the FSAA system scan successfully completing with the possible inclusion of a higher file depth scan depending on how many levels deep the path goes, with the addition of a successful FSAA Bulk Import will display the DFS file path structure within the AIC console. In my test environment I am able to UNC to my network share as well as running a search against that network share in the AIC. Once I made that path sharable on my DFS server and ran the necessary scans it built a file structure within the AIC which is the screenshot. I have also nested folders into my DFS Namespace Server and those folders are accessible within the AIC now as well. 





Thank you,

Scottie Taylor
